../../../../idea-exploration/ideas/atlas-idea-002.md:1:# Atlas Idea 002: Navier-Stokes Existence and Smoothness
../../../../idea-exploration/ideas/atlas-idea-002.md:5:The Navier-Stokes Existence and Smoothness problem is one of the seven Millennium Prize Problems ($1M prize). The question: given smooth initial conditions and a smooth forcing function, do solutions to the 3D incompressible Navier-Stokes equations always remain smooth for all time, or can they develop singularities (blow up)?
../../../../idea-exploration/ideas/atlas-idea-002.md:11:- **Tao (2016):** Constructed blow-up solutions for an averaged version of Navier-Stokes, showing that "generic" techniques cannot rule out blow-up — any proof must use specific structural properties of the nonlinearity.
../../../../idea-exploration/ideas/atlas-idea-002.md:18:- **Strong computational side:** Unlike pure algebra problems, Navier-Stokes has a rich numerical simulation tradition. Explorers can run fluid simulations, test blow-up candidates, measure scaling exponents, and verify claimed bounds computationally.
../../../../idea-exploration/ideas/atlas-idea-002.md:20:- **Estimate-tightening:** The Yang-Mills mission succeeded by finding that a key estimate (SZZ Lemma 4.1) was 8× too conservative. Navier-Stokes has analogous energy estimates (Ladyzhenskaya inequality, interpolation estimates) that may have similar slack.
