missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-004/attacks/chain-01.md:74:The chain claims to rank mechanisms spanning critical elements, tensor routes, Lagrangian routes, and possibly stochastic structures. Those routes have different currencies of progress: compactness, coercivity, localization stability, propagation, or dynamical rigidity. Without a common scoring rubric, "ranking" is largely evaluator preference disguised as output discipline.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-004/attacks/chain-02.md:13:- `L^3` is not just one more critical space on a list. It already sits next to very strong endpoint regularity results, so any minimal-element program there has to explain why those results do not already collapse the route or why the hypothetical critical element evades them only in a very specific way.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-004/attacks/chain-02.md:14:- `\dot H^{1/2}` has a cleaner Hilbert-space profile technology than `BMO^{-1}`, but it is less naturally tied to the suitable-weak-solution machinery that usually feeds local energy and backward-uniqueness style arguments.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-004/attacks/chain-02.md:15:- `BMO^{-1}` is the weakest candidate in this menu for a compactness-rigidity program. It is excellent for small-data mild theory, but it is a poor default host for a large-data minimal blowup extraction unless one can point to a concrete nonlinear profile decomposition and a robust stability theory in exactly that setting.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-004/attacks/chain-02.md:17:So the step's framing is too loose. "Rank realistic spaces" sounds harmless, but the real burden is to prove that at least one space supports the whole package: local theory, perturbation theory, profile decomposition, symmetry normalization, pressure control, and a notion of compactness compatible with the intended rigidity lever. A ranking memo can hide the fact that no candidate actually clears that bar.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-004/attacks/chain-02.md:27:- Requiring Tao-sensitivity before the extraction package is built biases the search toward novelty theater. It rewards mechanisms that sound NS-specific rather than mechanisms that can actually be applied to an almost-periodic critical element.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-004/attacks/chain-02.md:29:There is also a sequencing problem. In most compactness-rigidity programs, the hypothetical critical element tells you what rigidity information is even geometrically available. Here the chain asks for the rigidity weapon before it knows the target's regularity, compactness modulus, or pressure information. That is backwards.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-004/attacks/chain-02.md:37:- Formulating a minimal blowup object in Navier-Stokes is not bookkeeping. It requires a serious extraction package, not just a template borrowed from dispersive PDE.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-004/attacks/chain-02.md:43:The kill condition again sounds precise but is softer than it looks. A "clean formulation" can be written on paper while still relying on unproved profile decomposition, unproved critical stability, or an incompatible solution class. The step should fail unless the object is definable with a clear dependency graph to known results and one sharply identified missing theorem.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-004/attacks/chain-02.md:50:- Even if an almost-periodic critical element exists, it is far from obvious that the chosen lever is defined on that class, let alone strong enough to force triviality.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-004/attacks/chain-02.md:80:What is genuinely weak is that the chain has not identified a real Navier-Stokes rigidity mechanism yet. Until it does, the program is mostly a shell around the sentence: "maybe there is an NS-specific rigidity input that defeats the critical element." That is not false, but it is not enough to justify this chain as more than a disciplined placeholder.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-004/planner.md:21:Central premise: if local estimate routes are exhausted, the right object may be a minimal blowup solution, with exclusion driven by a rigidity mechanism that uses exact NS structure rather than harmonic-analysis closure.
runtime/results/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-decision-010-step-evaluator.md:8:The next step is scoped strictly to Chain Step 1: audit `L^3`, `\dot H^{1/2}`, and only if justified `BMO^{-1}` against a full extraction package, then either freeze one host space or stop the chain with a no-host obstruction.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-004/refined/chain-02.md:5:A compactness-rigidity route is only live if one specific critical or near-critical host space supports an explicit extraction package. The program should first audit that package theorem by theorem, then define the hypothetical critical element, and only then test rigidity quantities that are actually defined on that class.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-004/refined/chain-02.md:23:- Action: compare `L^3`, `\dot H^{1/2}`, and only if justified `BMO^{-1}` against an explicit checklist: local theory in the intended solution framework, large-data perturbation or stability, profile decomposition or equivalent extraction input, symmetry normalization, pressure or local-energy compatibility, and a compactness notion usable by the later rigidity step.
