missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-03.md:15:- The candidate list (`L^3`, `dot H^{1/2}`, `BMO^{-1}`) mixes spaces with very different compactness, stability, and uniqueness behavior, but the step acts as if "extraction feasibility" is a comparable scalar score. It is not. A space can be good for mild-solution local theory and still be bad for the kind of precompactness modulo symmetry that a critical-element scheme needs.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-03.md:17:- `BMO^{-1}` is especially suspect here. It is natural for small-data theory, but as a habitat for a minimal blowup object it is weak, nonlocal, and poorly matched to the kind of pointwise or geometric rigidity mechanisms later advertised.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-03.md:18:- `L^3` and `dot H^{1/2}` are more realistic, but the chain does not state what notion of solution is being minimized over, what continuation criterion defines the threshold, or what stability theory is assumed. Without that, "rank realistic candidate spaces" is premature.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-03.md:31:- "Formulate the hypothetical minimal blowup object" makes it sound as if the object is available once a space is chosen. In reality, this step may already require a profile decomposition, nonlinear perturbation theory, stability under the chosen topology, and a sharp threshold definition compatible with Navier-Stokes scaling.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-03.md:51:- The kill condition is again too compressed. A route can fail for reasons other than collapsing to Tao-preserved structure: wrong solution class, no time directionality, non-closedness under limits, incompatibility with almost-periodic scaling, or the need for extra decay that a critical element will not have.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-03.md:94:That template is powerful, but here it may be more a framing trap than a guide. The chain assumes that if local mechanism hunts fail, the right global object is a minimal blowup profile. That is a substantive bet, not a neutral fallback. Navier-Stokes may resist this style of attack precisely because the available rigidity inputs are too weak or too noncritical to close the loop.
