./runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-run-001-attacker-01.log:531:./runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-run-001-planner.log:764:/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/vasseur-pressure/CHAIN.md:70:**Critical context:** Compensated compactness (Coifman-Lions-Meyer-Semmes) gives p = div(u tensor u) in H^1(R^3), NOT a better L^p exponent. H^1 is contained in L^1 which is contained in L^{4/3} in terms of Lebesgue inclusion. The question is whether the H^1 structure (cancellation, atomic decomposition) can be converted into something the De Giorgi machine can use that raw L^{4/3} cannot provide.
./runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-run-001-attacker-01.log:588:./runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-run-001-planner.log:851:/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/vasseur-pressure/steps/step-002/RESULTS.md:21:**Devastating bonus:** Even with hypothetical W^{1,3} regularity (||∇u||_{L^3} available), H^1-BMO gives |I_p| ≤ C·E_0·2^k (no U_k factor), while Hölder gives |I_p| ≤ C·E_0·2^k·U_k^{1/2} (with U_k factor). Hölder wins even with better regularity. **H^1-BMO is structurally inappropriate for De Giorgi**, not just insufficient due to Leray-Hopf limitations.
